text:
"i always thought i didn't have what it takes to be president. i always thought it took a certain level of dignity." @crissle (2018)
*
*
"when i was a kid, i thought the president had to be the most organized, most rational...i thought you had to be a magnificent bitch. i never thought that the president could openly discuss sexually assaulting women and it be ok. i never thought the president could mock sexually assaulting women." @kidfury (2018)
*
*
byrd’s image of whiteness as a product of slavery, incest, and rape was echoed by thomas jefferson, writing the lawyer francis gray in 1815: “you asked me in conversation, what constituted a mulatto by our law? and i believe i told you four crossings with the whites. i looked afterwards into our law, and found that one-fourth of negro blood, mixed with any portion of white, constitutes the mulatto.” jefferson initially abstracted his discussion into an enlightenment era flurry of algebraic equations, likening the laws of blood proportion to “a mathematical problem of the same class with those on the mixtures of different liquors or different metals.” soon, though, he switched to language eerily reminiscent of byrd’s, analogizing to “a merino ram being crossed, first with a country ewe, second with his daughter, third with his granddaughter, and fourth with his great-granddaughter, the last issue being deemed pure merino, having in fact but 1/16 of the country blood.” jefferson then took a short step from “country blood” to the number of “crosses with the pure white” that “clears the issue of the negro blood.” although one whose blood has been “cleared” is not automatically free under “the principle of the civil law, partus sequitur ventrem,” jefferson wrote, “if he be emancipated, he becomes a free white man, and a citizen of the united states to all incidents and purposes. jefferson did not bemoan the idea that citizens of african descent can become...white.
*
*
'crossing the color line: racial migration and the one-drop rule, 1600–1860' by daniel sharfstein (2015)
*
*

text:
rebuilding is hard. not a day goes by where i dontnlearn something new, or handle something i have never before gone through. i just feel so alone so often. observing everything around me. wanting to meet people, but not knowing what to talk about, or not being aware of the subject. like literally, its music i havent heard, movies i havent seen, places i havent been, people i dont know, lables i've never heard of, dont get me starting on the dating and how beautifully diverse of a community is out there. i've even forgotten some of what i knew before him. then theres my brain and how it is just now clearing the clouds of ptsd that help make thinking, functioning, feeling, and remembering hard. 
i get so overwhelmed, and just feel disconnected from society. please, please teach me, dont judge me or expect me to know. i need help, support, love, etc. i'm healing, please help me survive and live. because frankly, it's a lot to take on alone. 💜 #domesticviolencerecovery  #domesticviolenceawarenessmonth #domesticviolence #abuserecovery #endthesilenceondomesticviolence #talkaboutit #recovery #mystory #abusesurvivor #survivor #survivortosurvivor #support #lifetransformation #healing #lgbtq #metoo #love

text:
after last week, it’s hard to argue that women in the us have achieved equality. 44 of the 50 senators who ignored dr. ford’s heart-wrenching testimony and confirmed kavanaugh were men. does that sound like equal power and opportunities to you? sure doesn’t to us!
this #internationaldayofthegirl let’s take a collective vow to do better to address gender equality right here at home. 
and let’s remember - this is not a women’s issue. gender diverse companies perform better. gender diverse governments are less corrupt. gender equal countries have happier kids. 
it’s time we all—men, women, gender fluid—vow to stand against inequality and discrimination wherever we see it. we rise or fall as one nation - let’s rise.

text:
in support of the #metoo movement. 
i have been following the #metoo movement in india silently ever since it began. i have been reading reactions, responses or the lack of them by the alleged assaulters and abusers.  i have also been listening  to conversations and arguments of why it was not brought forward earlier and why are these women speaking now. 
if you haven’t experienced sexual assault, abuse or harassment, then you have no idea of what it’s like to be in their shoes. hence you have no right to judge how they addressed it then  or are addressing it now. 
earlier today i shared a link to an article on my fb profile about the reasons why women wouldn’t have spoken up earlier.

i just had to write this in support of all women sharing their stories of sexual abuse and assault. thank you for mustering the courage to speak up now. better late than never. and no, it is not washing your dirty laundry in public. don’t let any one convince you of that ! each of you(us) who are speaking up now are inspiring other women to do the same. 
let us allow and give space for the system to be exposed to its depth and for it  it to be addressed and healed as this is the society and culture we are leaving behind for sons and daughters. 
there is a saying in malayalam which roughly translates as- “don’t  keep rolling around in the muck you have fallen in”. pick up yourself, admit that you had a fall or were pushed dust yourself and get moving. 
there were a few responses that caught my eye especially the ones of chetan bhagat and raghu dixit. i am quoting their names as i want to acknowledge their response. it’s at least a start, even though some words used their their response still don’t make sense. 
nothing can justify a act of assault, abuse or harassment. it’s a huge invasion into one’s personal boundary and it also mirrors the lack of respect one have towards another human being. 
having said that, it makes are huge difference to me as reader, a # metoo supporter and a woman, when men take personal responsibility for their impact, apologize and own to their actions rather than resort to cheap, below the belt tactics. 
#metoo #metoomovement #metooindia

text:
overcoming abuse labeled me a difficult child and woman.
.
.
my parents called me a difficult child countless times because...
.
.
i have never accepted their norm of abuse. .
.
i have never accepted the world’s opinion to settle for less.
.
.
if there was hope of an easier, more peaceful solution to the problem in front of me, i have pursued it relentlessly.
.
.
regardless of the criticism from those around me.
.
.
in the pursuit of peace and happiness, i have overcome the cycle of abuse that i was raised with. .
.
and the result is i now live a life filled with joy, peace, hope, and opportunity.
.
.
if you are living with a situation that makes you feel small, guilty, ashamed, belittled, hopeless… please know there is help available to you and a life of peace available to you, too.
.
.
the tenacity, resilience, and determination that i had to learn as a child has taught me to persevere until i have overcome the situation. .
.
i’ve used this perseverance to reverse chronic illness. i teach this perseverance and how to overcome to my clients so they achieve their dream goals do more money, love, a better job, a better marriage, easier parenting, more personal time for themselves, whatever their goals... it works.
.
.
you can have a life of freedom to! you may need a little more support to get there. email me and we can talk about how to achieve your dreams.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
may not a single more girl/woman ever again get told, "hush! don't talk like that!" ✋✋🔥👁💜
and finally, that -- which i just wasn't planning to speak on. not because it isn't important to support the movement. it is! but because it's an event way too old in my life, and more importantly, because it's one i have completely got over. healed from. released. 💜💜👁
.
of course, after working through tremendous #trauma , #bodyshame and physical aftermaths too. i till date struggle with certain other associated cognitive dissonance and dysfunctional shadow side that are common to any #abusesurvivor .. and that's why this #metoomovement
is very very relevant to the subject of #mentalhealth too.
.
any abuse and more so physical /sexual abuse, scars an individual way beyond the body, deep upto the psyche. it damages one's  self perception self confidence and the ability to self-love too, in complex and layered ways. 
such acts destroy one's psychological and overall #healthandwellness to an unspeakable extent. 
so. if you have struggled with such incidents i hope and pray you find all the strength and courage to speak up. alternatively, if you know a friend or family member who's gone through this and needs your support, please hold space for them to open up. 💜💙 our world is rapidly shifting. our collective #awareness evolving to greater transparency and #responsibility.. let's hold space for one another and promote more social and systemic #transformation 🙏💜💙👁
.
.
.
.
.

text: as we ‘celebrate’ the international day of the girl, i think about all the ways i raised the kid to be independent, to explore her interests, indulge her passions, and to feel empowered with regard to owning her body and feeling free to make her own decisions. this is a luxury not every girl child has. as stated on the un website on this day (see link in bio) across the world girls face adversities that hinder their education, training and entry into their workforce. they have less access to information, communication technology and resources, such as the internet. i am lucky to have had many role models in my mother and her 7 sisters (in their 70’s and 80’s) who were pioneers in their generation, getting graduate degrees, traveling and living across the world for education and career and integrating motherhood and career. in this the age of #metoo and persistent pay inequities we all have a part to play in creating a world where girls thrive. this november americans need to vote for people who are concerned with issues that impact girls and women. ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ #internationaldayofthegirl #girlpower #dayofthegirl #girlz #blackgirlmagic #girlsrock #motherhood #raisingdaughters #raisinggirls #strongwomen #badassgirls #motherdaughter #mygirl #twinning #melaninpoppin #vote #feminism #feminist #feminista #fiftyplus #fiftypluslife #fiftyplusliving #fiftypluslifestyle

text: i morgen holder jeg oplæg om #metoo til kulturnatten i cinemateket. temaet er “den røde løber”, og der er lagt op til en festlig aften. men selvom der er meget at fejre et år efter, at denne længe imødesete sociale revolution blev sat i gang af to små ord og et hashtag, så byder næsten hver dag på nye, deprimerende historier om magtmisbrug, chikane og overgreb. det kæmpestore containerskib,  som filmverden er, lastet med kulturelle spejlinger og eksistensværdier, er langsomt ved at ændre kurs. vi er på rette vej, men vi er ikke kommet i land endnu. derfor må vi blive ved og ved at tale om det, hjemme i stuerne og på den røde løber. ::: i denne uge kan du her følge @nannafrankrasmussen, der deler tanker om sin feministisk hverdag :::

text:
i was assaulted at 8 years old in a mall.... i escaped miraculously. i was assaulted again at 19 in the street at night, walking by myself, i fought and run to meet my dad. i told him was happened and he tried to find the guy... no luck. i was almost raped by a coworker in a hotel in spain. when i tried to tell my boss she told me to say nothing, he was a pilot and i was going to get fired in a second. so i kept it to myself, like many of us other flight attendants. i never talked about these things before, why? shame. shame on us for being such whores. as much you think it’s hard for you guys, sorry, we still get it worse.

text: to those that think sexual abuse should just be forgotten as we age.............."the overall picture that emerges when the sexually abused females are compared with the matched comparison females is that females who experienced sexual abuse are different (on average) across many of these biopsychosocial domains. they differ in their interpersonal and sexual behaviors and social networks. they are biologically changed with lower resting levels of cortisol, asymmetrical stress responses, and abnormal physical development including increased rates of obesity and earlier onsets of puberty. they have cognitive deficits in fluid and crystallized abilities. they think about things differently, especially sex. they are more likely to be depressed, to have ptsd and dissociative symptoms, to be physically and sexually revictimized, to be involved with an abusive partner, to become a teen mother and to have a premature baby. they are more likely to engage in self-mutilation, risky sexual activity, abuse drugs and alcohol, experience more lifetime traumas, fail to complete high school, and qualify for at least one dsm diagnosis. as parents, they place their children at increased risk for abuse and neglect and overall maldevelopment as they repeat generational patterns of abuse, neglect, and family dysfunction. there is evidence of immune system dysfunction as well as evidence for increased levels of catecholamines. the abused females had significantly higher levels of somatic symptoms at several assessment points and reported more medical visits, more major illnesses and hospitalizations than comparison females". #metoo #menopausemedic #mypurpose #enoughisenough #timesup #girlpower #sexualabuse #survivor #nomeansno #internationaldayofthegirl  https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/pmc3693773/

text:
another wave of #metoo hits big deals in pakistan; girls alleging pakistan s heavy weights. popular socialmedia sensation and stand-up comedian junaid akram and late great philanthropist of pakistan abdul sattar edhi’s son and now the chairman of the edhi foundation faisal edhi are being accused with the allegations of sexual harassment and molestations.

few days ago, anchorperson and female journalist rabia anum took to the twitter with some disturbing revelation; without taking the name of the culprit, she mentioned several girls have approached to her along with proofs and evidences against the famous stand-up-comedian.

several people while retweeting rabia anum’s tweet come up with their experiences and the conclusion surfaces that it was none other than the stand-up comedian, social media activist and actor junaid akram.

on the other hand, another series of tweet has taken the internet by storm when a former journalist urooj zia took to the twitter and in a long thread revealed some shocking and appalling series of harrowing events while alleging famous philanthropist faisal edhi of sexual harassment from her memories.

recounting the harrowing memories, urooj zia went on with details that faisal edhi a few years back after an interview had tried to get cozy with her, touched her inappropriately, texted her late night and other acts that intimidated her that time. this made urooj puzzled and instead of shaming him on spot, she fell prey of the thought that it must be some of her own wrongdoing that wreak such havoc to her.

text:
today is #internationaldayofthegirl . i’m happy my daughter is growing up in an age where we are continuing to push for our rights as women. our voices, more then ever are louder and prouder then they’ve ever been. we continue to push for our rights that our predecessors before us, fought so hard for. the movement continues and i hope that my daughter will be part of the next generation to continue pushing for our rights as women. 
i’m proud that she is growing up in the #metoo movement. and i’m proud of all the women are finding there strength and speaking up about their experiences. i’m glad women are no longer blaming themselves for what has happened to them. i’m proud women are teaching their sons how to treat women. and i’m proud of all the men who are stepping up and supporting women. 
i’m proud i have a daughter that will one day be just as successful as my sons and treated just as they are. they may be different genders but in the end we are all just human.
#supporteachother #love #girlsrock #womensempowerment #womenempoweringgirls #internationdayofthegirl2018

text:
the grace tree foundation will be offering trauma sensitive yoga in the sweet soul yoga studio beginning this sunday from 2-3pm. if you are a survivor of sexual assault, or an ally of someone who is, please join them for this nourishing yoga practice. sign up by contacting thegracetreefoundation@gmail.com.
suggested donation is $10.
future classes will be held on the following sundays from 2-3pm: oct 28, nov 4, 18, 25, and dec 2.
all levels and beginners are welcome.

text: it’s cathartic to rewrite hymns and make them relevant to the struggles faced by so many today. i’m working on a large project rewriting hymns tackling lots of current social justice issues, but this one got me through the relived trauma of last week. women who have endured through the waste deep anxiety, pain and rage of sexual assault, i see you. i hear you. can you imagine an entire group singing our validation?! it makes me smile. hymn were once powerful tools (not that they aren’t now, but so many people are simply disconnected from them.) here’s my thoughts- tune: come thou fount #rewritehymns #hymns #socialjusticehymn #metoo #metoohymn @stephenathome @colbertlateshow @glennondoyle @sarcasticlutheran @brenebrown @huffpostwomen

text:
“ by empowering a woman, we empower a child. by educating a girl child, we make it possible for her to grow up to become an empowered woman.
- winnie byanyima :
:

today is international day of the girl. with this year’s theme being “ a skilled girlforce”
:
what is this initiative? “since 2012, 11 october has been marked as the international day of the girl. the day aims to highlight and address the needs and challenges girls face, while promoting girls' empowerment and the fulfillment of their human rights.”
:
:
:
:
i’m participating in this movement because as girl growing up in jamaica i was never told i “couldn’t” my resources were limited but my dreams were immense. i was lucky enough to have parents who believed in “following your own path.” many girls in the third world do not have that luxury and are forced into less than favourable situations daily.
:
:
:
:
:
you may think globally but act locally by getting involve with your local/international organizations to help facilitate education, health and other pressing needs girls face daily. confident girls today empowered women tomorrow.
for more information 
http://www.un.org/en/events/girlchild/
@unitednations

text:
sexual assault: unilag turn  deaf ears to sexual harassment allegations.
.
the management of the university of lagos, akoka, has kept mum on the investigation of one of their lecturers.

it was reported in may that joy nwana, a student of the university, accused mr awonusi, who was also a former vice chancellor of tai solarin university of education, of demanding sex for mark.

the institution also appealed to linda ikeji blog, who first reported the story, to assist in convincing ms nwana, the lady in question to defend her sexual harassment claim.

other universities who suffered such embarrassing fate this year, specifically obafemi awolowo university and lagos state university have taken proactive measures by dismissing the randy lecturers.

however, three months after unilag’s vc addressed a conference on ms nwana’s allegations, the university has refused to make known if it has taken further steps.

the institution’s principal assistant registrar, communication’s unit, taiwo oloyede, in a telephone interview on wednesday had no new information on the scandal.
“after the press conference the vc held, i have not heard anything about the matter,” she said.

"63% of women say they will vote democratic. women are also more enthusiastic about voting this year than men, an important shift from previous elections.
in other words, any impending democratic victory will likely be thanks to women. but we aren't just voting. a record number of us are running for office this year. female donors are giving more money than ever to midterm races. we are working on campaigns, door-knocking, fundraising, and showing up at marches and protests." #trumpchicken 🐥

text:
g i r l s ☆ „(...) ich hoffe und wünsche mir für alle mädchen auf der welt, dass es den weltmädchentag eines tages nicht mehr wird geben müssen, um darauf aufmerksam zu machen, dass wir noch immer in einer welt leben, in der mädchen und jungs, frauen und männer nicht wirklich gleich sind. in einer welt mit pay-gaps und #metoo, in einer welt, in der bullies und vergewaltiger die höchsten posten der regierung eines landes bekleiden können, während für alles, was sie auf ihrem weg zur macht getan haben, eine entschuldigung gefunden wird. in einer welt, in der die privilegien von männern immer noch höher bewertet werden, als die körperliche und seelische unversehrtheit von frauen.
bis es soweit ist, lasst uns unsere töchter zu starken frauen erziehen, die wissen, was sie wert sind wie sie den mund aufmachen für ihre rechte und die anderer. und lasst uns unsere söhne zu liebevollen empathischen männern erziehen und leben wir ihnen vor, wie man gleichberechtigt und respektvoll miteinander lebt und nicht einen ewigen machtkampf, in dem es immer einen gewinner geben muss – und eine verliererin.“

text:
elle: mia farrow takes an unflinching look at her past in the wake of the #metoo movement

at the maharishi’s compound in rishikesh, india, by the way, farrow did find that his practices helped her regain a foothold in the world. but soon the calm of his ashram was shattered by the arrival of the beatles—photographers scrambled into trees trying to get a shot. in the days that followed, the beatles wrote “dear prudence” for farrow’s sister. then, after a private meditation session, the maharishi made an unwelcome advance on farrow. “suddenly i became aware of two surprisingly male, hairy arms going around me,” she writes. she immediately left the ashram. and in keeping with the ways farrow’s life has twisted through a trivia night’s worth of events, this encounter also set in motion the beatles’ break with the guru. their song “sexy sadie,” about a woman who made a fool of everyone, was originally titled “maharishi.”
#maharishi #tm #miafarrow #transcendentalmeditation

text:
when i was a girl, i didn’t take off my wonder woman underoos for a year because i swore they gave me special powers. when i was a girl, i had two incredible parents who helped me believe that i was capable of doing anything i put my mind to. when i was a girl, i did all the things reserved for boys and shone bright. it was only when i became a woman that i learned that the little bubble of empowerment that i was raised in was a far cry from the way the world looked at me. i was bullied by girls and objectified by boys, and then by women and men, for the way i looked and acted, and how it made them feel. i shifted. i became smaller. i hid my thoughts, my feelings, my strength, and my body so i wouldn’t make waves. i lost my voice. i lost my inner wonder woman.
🎙
then one day, somehow, i woke up. i was tired of hiding. tired of keeping the peace. tired of playing it safe. tired of being mediocre. tired of being silent. tired of hiding that fierce girl in the #wonderwoman underoos. i left my marriage. i started a new career and life. i started using my voice. i started living in my truth. i started working with girls to help them find theirs. and then, these past couple years, i started getting mad. mad that we elected a man to the highest office who makes women feel like second class citizens through his words, actions, and example. a bully, a misogynist, and a straight up perv. a man who boys and girls are supposed to look up to, who reinforces all the things that made me feel small as i came of age. a man who tells us we don’t matter and are not to be believed by backing and praising a man like kavanaugh. mad that we live in a society where more people, many many men and women alike, aren’t fucking furious. mad that i have to explain and justify my anger, even to people i just assumed would be angry right with me.
🖤
this #internationaldayofthegirl - fight for the girls in wonder woman underoos, make sure they feel and stay empowered even in today’s political climate. use your voice to help them navigate the journey to womanhood. lift them up and work to create a world where they won’t have to fight for equality, and where they won’t have to say #metoo , ever.

text:
free event alert 🚨 i’ve been thinking a lot about how lucky i am to be able to go to 12 step meetings and share authentically about what’s going on in my life with other strangers who understand. in the wake of all the news, i’ve been realizing i don’t have that same space to talk about trauma and how i feel surround by people who understand....and maybe you don’t either?!
.
.
so i decided to change that! on sunday october 21st at 1pm i’m hosting a free support group at my office for any woman who would like to join me and have a safe space to process what’s been going in the wake of #drford and #kavanaugh and be around other women who understand and relate. whether you are a client or not, you are invited and welcome. come as you are! coffee and light refreshments will be available! email amanda@amandaewhite.com to reserve your spot. space is limited! #womensupportingwomen

text: alison wonderland, i feel, is a beacon of strength for all females who want to make it in an industry where the women to men ratio is imbalanced. i think she absolutely slays, and watching her journey has inspired me so much. because of the issues in today’s world, and the strength she represents, all proceeds of this top will go towards the time’s up now fund, effective 10/11/18 until the top runs out. crops are almost sold out across the shop, and heading into the fall and winter months new styles will be debuted, where this donation will continue to be in effect. as a victim of sexual assault myself, this topic hits home, and if i can do something, even if it’s small, to make a difference, then i will. i encourage everyone to do the same towards what they care about. we need to bring the same love and passion we have at these festivals and shows to our every day lives, and spread it as far as we can. thank you 🙏🤗💓

text:
“but she always has a smile on her face” 
today i thank the angel that gave me the courage to reach out for help a little more today 💕 today marks two years since i decided, 6 days before my 19th bday, that life wasn’t for me. today marks the day i stop counting the days since i did it & turning them into days i’ve become stronger & built the best life i can for myself. after enduring the worst 8 years of my childhood to sexual abuse, to depression, to self harm, to ptsd, to anxiety of all sorts. to a 4 year fight with the law counts & counting. to medicine that never cured me. to a room with a table & a therapist that turned things around. to the ones who left, thank you. & the ones who stayed, thank you even more. i would have never imagined i’d be loved by the people that love me today or be where i am today. too be loved by my best friends & my family. to have such a support group i never have to be where i used to be ever again. to renting my own place at just 20. to be able to look at myself every morning & remind myself that it’s not my fault & it never has been nor will never be as much as it’s not your fault & will never be. #metoo i have such confidence & love i’ve never had before, towards myself & life. to just be genuinely happy at night when i lay my head down every night. i’ve turned “i should’ve tried harder” to “thank god im not dead” in two years & that might be my biggest accomplishment. things work out for reasons & things don’t work out for reasons. i’m the happiest & the healthiest i’ve ever been in 10+ years. life gets better, you just need to be alive to see it. i know what it’s like to feel like the whole world is under you & i know what it feels like to cry every night wishing you don’t wake up. i know what it’s like to feel like you have no one. but you are truly never alone. check up on your loved ones because the ones who smile the most, need a hand. & if i could tell my younger self what i know now, i would’ve never done what i did. but you grow & you learn. it’s a long & hard battle but i can promise you, once you see the light at the end of the tunnel, you’re gonna do amazing things. #mentalhealth #endthestigma

text: i haven't said much lately, but today i could no longer keep silent. i watched every hearing, listened as certain government leaders and others either defended or denied the allegations surrounding kavanaugh. i watched as dr. ford recounted her attack and sat wondering what has become of america. women everywhere including me, have been victims of sexual assault and too often don't tell, aren't believed, or so ashamed we pretend it never happened. today is the last day to register to vote. pleeesssssssseeeeeeee register. i know it can seem like our voices don't matter in this climate, but they do! today i ask us to step up and speak out for those who feel they can't. let's stand together! #unshakeable #metoo #bethechurchyouwanttosee

text:
today marks the 1 year anniversary of the #metoo movement. i’ve never shared my story, but it should be no surprise that i have one. every 98 seconds in america someone is sexually assaulted, and  every 8 minutes, that victim is a child. the sad part is only 6 out of 1000 perpetrators will be imprisoned. everyone women i know has their only story. it hasn’t happened once to me, it’s happened several times. i can talk about a few openly, but that’s only been recently, one incident i’ve never spoken of to anyone & truthfully i don’t know if i ever will. one time while staying at a friends house i feel asleep in his bed, i woke up to him penetrating me, there was no consent there, i was a sleep, and i woke up while it was happening, i went along bc i was scared & didn’t know what to do. i had never even kissed this person before. there was  the time my boyfriend beat & strangled me then held me down while i screamed no & raped me. there are the times i drank too much and have no memory at all & just felt sheer embarrassment the next day, even though i was clearly not in my right mind to give consent. to this day i don’t remember even a moment of it & never talk about it. the one that i can’t share happened when i was a child with a family friend & it’s the one that haunts me the most. maybe one day i’ll be able to talk about, but today that is all i feel safe to share. i’m sorry to all the women who’ve been through similar things. i can’t say i know exactly your pain bc every experience is different, but i’ll always try to understand & be there for you! i love you all & be safe! 😘

text:
after a year of headlines,
#metoo is everywhere.
it has left a scathing mark worldwide.
twitter is exploding with allegations of sexual harrasments and everyone around the globe is expressing their anxiety and dismay.
the fair sex are sharing their harrasment cases in every field - journalism, film industry, workplace, politics and the list follows... some men won't change and will never respect a women's dignity and never stop treating them as their sex objects.
(don't call me a womanist, for i don't mean all men, i'm just raising my voice against the assaulters.) we always have a misconception right, that being an actress is easy or specifically living a movie star's life?
ever heard of 'casting couch?' the main and the most traumatic ingredient of film industry - where female debutant's are asked to seduce their directors to grab a role in movies. nevertheless, journalism offers you the same. also, how to forget the adventurous air-hostess profession, where juniors are asked to sleep with senior pilots and ground staffs to get promotion.

and even after such behaviour, 'we' choose to keep quiet, suffer in this manner but never take a stand for ourselves. why? because 'chaar logon k saamne hamari aur hamare parivar ki bezzati ho jaegi'. our majestic supreme court striked down #section377 and #section497. but in the rising cases against women, there is an alarming need to criminalize these unorthodox practices including rape. we just don't need an order stating, 'death penalty for rapes under the pocso act', but we need real actions against it.
you can rationalise your order stating:
"no girl will feel good seeing her father, brother or uncle hanging to death in front of their eyes",
but you never asked those fathers, brothers or uncles if they even feel anything while treating other's daughters or sisters with such disgrace.
i am not taking sides of the projected victims. i don't know their full story. but if it's true, then please stop defending the culprits.

defending men is easy, taking action against them is tough and that's where our country is failing to overcome the shameful crimes.

#metoo #metoo #metoo

बहुतेक अंधाराला चेहरा नसतो म्हणून अंधारात कोणी मदतीसाठी हाक मारली, किंवा वेदनेनं किंचाळलं जरी, तरी सुद्धा हा समाज त्या हाकेला साद देत नाही. पण म्हणून अंधारात घडलेला अत्याचार, त्या घटना, मदतीसाठी मारलेली हाक या समाजाला नाकारता येणार नाही. आपल्या समाजात स्त्रियांवर अत्याचार होतात, मग ते कुटुंबात, कामाच्या ठिकाणी किंवा इतर ठिकाणी होत असतील. यामध्ये छेडछाड करण्यापासून ते बलात्कार करून मारून टाकण्यापर्यंतचे प्रकार होतात. बऱ्याचदा पीडित महिला त्याबद्दल बोलत नाही, बऱ्याचश्या घटना समोर येत नाहीत. पण म्हणून त्यांच्यावर झालेला अन्याय - अत्याचार आपल्याला नाकारता येणार नाही. सध्या #metoo च्या निमित्ताने काही महिला त्यांच्या बाबतीत घडलेल्या गैरप्रकाराबद्दल बोलत आहेत. त्यात सत्य-असत्य किती? हे चौकशी नंतर पुढे येईल, दोषींना कायद्याप्रमाणे शिक्षाही होईल. 
सध्या आपण या चळवळीकडे सकारात्मक दृष्टीने बघण्याची गरज आहे. अन्यायाविरुद्धचा आवाज बुलंद करण्याची गरज आहे.
#i_support #me_too (आणि या #metoo चळवळीबद्दल सरसकटपणे नकारात्मक टिपण्णी करणारे किंवा त्याची टिंगल टवाळी करणाऱ्यांना या गोष्टीच गांभीर्य कळलेलं नाही, असं मला वाटतं.)
name: Lahu Arekar

stop_filter_tweet: ीला_बोलायचंय बहुतेक अंधाराला चेहरा नसतो म्हणून अंधारात कोणी मदतीसाठी हाक मारली , किंवा वेदनेनं किंचाळलं जरी , तरी सुद्धा हा समाज त्या हाकेला साद देत नाही . पण म्हणून अंधारात घडलेला अत्याचार , त्या घटना , मदतीसाठी मारलेली हाक या समाजाला नाकारता येणार नाही . आपल्या समाजात स्त्रियांवर अत्याचार होतात , मग ते कुटुंबात , कामाच्या ठिकाणी किंवा इतर ठिकाणी होत असतील . यामध्ये छेडछाड करण्यापासून ते बलात्कार करून मारून टाकण्यापर्यंतचे प्रकार होतात . बऱ्याचदा पीडित महिला त्याबद्दल बोलत नाही , बऱ्याचश्या घटना समोर येत नाहीत . पण म्हणून त्यांच्यावर झालेला अन्याय - अत्याचार आपल्याला नाकारता येणार नाही . सध्या च्या निमित्ताने काही महिला त्यांच्या बाबतीत घडलेल्या गैरप्रकाराबद्दल बोलत आहेत . त्यात सत्य-असत्य किती ? हे चौकशी नंतर पुढे येईल , दोषींना कायद्याप्रमाणे शिक्षाही होईल . सध्या आपण या चळवळीकडे सकारात्मक दृष्टीने बघण्याची गरज आहे . अन्यायाविरुद्धचा आवाज बुलंद करण्याची गरज आहे . ( आणि या चळवळीबद्दल सरसकटपणे नकारात्मक टिपण्णी करणारे किंवा त्याची टिंगल टवाळी करणाऱ्यांना या गोष्टीच गांभीर्य कळलेलं नाही , असं मला वाटतं . )

text: #metoo i wanted to write on this topic since a long time but i wasn't really confident whether i should write it or not. but then i thought when men feel no shame in raping women why should i feel shame in writing about it. yes, the afisa bano case touched me as well. and i made a few researches and concluded few reasons for the rising number of rapes in our country in the last two decades. okay, so let's start by imagining a rape. what comes to your mind when you think about a rape? a girl-  tied on to something, naked, being touched anywhere by some random guys, pleading them to stop and so on and so forth. i'm right, ain't i? but how can we imagine this when we haven't witnessed rape itself? there's something open in our incognito tabs on our phones- porn. yes that's true bondage porn has been adding something to rapes in the past few years because that's the time india developed internet. our day to day lifestyle has been influenced by movies, even our clothes are influenced by that. and sadly rapes have been influenced by hardcore bondage porn. now please don't raise questions about wtf was i doing on a pornsite.  secondly, the way society looks up at women. i remember when nirbhaya gang rape took place there was some workshop arranged by gujarat police in our school. i was in 9th standard by then. and guess what we were shown a short film and we're told to keep our body fully covered all the time as a measure of preventing the chances of getting raped. now may i please ask a question- i was wearing a school uniform, my body was fully covered, my hair were oiled & tightly braided into two braids, i was walking back home from school- why was i still eve teased on an isolated street (ps- i was in 9th standard and had almost no breast and ass). the thing is that we never actually blamed the criminal, instead when a girl gets eveteased and tells this to her parents- it's like she did something wrong. literally after that my all the few outings i was engaged in were banned and my dad used to pick me up and drop off at the school. i felt like a prisoner. cont. in comments.

text:
coming from a narcissist family can be confusing. you were made to believe that these seemingly “bad” behaviors are the problem when the double standard is usually at play. start your exit prep now so you no longer have to be the identified patient. it isn’t easy and may take a lifetime if you are the scapegoat of a narcissist family, but you can and will get past that. you can break out of the personality disorder dysfunction and possible cure yours if you have it. you have the power now to change these damaging thought patterns. who cares about what they’ll say about you. go to therapy. practice mindfulness. recognize you need help. change your behaviors and thought patterns slowly. you can do this. you are the master of your mind. take control. you are worthy. you are good enough. the only person you know for sure that you’ll take to the grave is yourself. i wish you the best. all is calm. the storm is over. you can start to swim now. you are worthy.
*
*
*

text: super excited to be displaying these two #darkroom prints in a show at the @lakewoodculturalcenter ! it’s been a while since i’ve been in a show of this caliber and i am so #honored to be chosen. it is a #portrait show, these are obvious #selfportraits of myself that came from a dark place, but also a place of #healing. it was terrifying the first time i showed this work to a public audience, i couldn’t even speak about it at that time and it took a couple years to be able to do so, but i know that it is important that my #work is seen by others who may have suffered from the same #abuse as me. i was #married one year to a #manipulative, #controlling, #lying, and #abusive man, if that’s what you want to call him. but he’s far from a man, he’s a coward and he is lost. when i was finally was able to leave him mentally and physically i started back in school and my professors told me to #create from within my #soul, all i could really find in there was a #sadness, a loss of myself, and these tiny pieces of me were still there and i had to put them back together so i could be me again. so i could be happy, so i could love, so i could love myself. this series of photos represents those pieces and putting them back together but honoring where i came from and knowing that the one good thing that came from that relationship was this, it was my art, it was the new me, it was a #stronger #me, it was the me that could help other women. there’s more to the #story that i’m trying to find the courage to share because i have seen so many of my beautiful and courageous friends share their stories lately. i haven’t been able to do it yet but i’m hoping i will. partly because i’m afraid of that person still and partly because i have a wonderful man who loves me like no one ever has. trying to move on but i realize i have something important to say still. #metoo #woman #feminist #mrslivingston #womenforwomen #love #abuse #survivor #arttherapy #femaleempowerment #ourstories #riseup

text:
this coming monday, october 15th marks the one year anniversary of the #metoo that went viral all over social media! 
if you don’t remember thousands+ women/men made their statues #metoo to spread sexual assault awareness. every 98 seconds an american is sexually assaulted 😳 individuals between ages 12-34 are at the highest risk! 
i personally encourage you to spread the #metoo awareness again this coming monday, october 15th and check out the  rainn organization! if you or someone you know needs a little hope, encouragement, community after being sexually assaulted please lead them to @rainn  share and spread the awareness 🌍

text:
*** neuerscheinung ***
jetzt auch als taschenbuch!

er hat mich geschändet.
er hat mich zerstört.
aber ich habe trotzdem überlebt!

klappentext:
du kannst menschen immer nur vor den kopf schauen. du siehst ihre maske, die sie dich sehen lassen wollen.

hannah hat keine freunde in der schule. sie ist eine außenseiterin und wird gemobbt. ihre noten sind gut und ihr elternhaus behütet. trotzdem lernt sie bereits in frühen jahren eine seite vom leben kennen, die man niemals erleben möchte. sie gerät in eine emotionale abhängigkeit zu einem jungen mann, der nicht nur ihren körper, sondern auch ihre seele verkauft.

ein roman über emotionale gewalt, zwangsprostitution, verstörende rituale und eine parallelgesellschaft, die sich mitten unter uns befindet.

teil 1 von 3

hannah hat keine freunde in der schule. sie ist eine außenseiterin und wird gemobbt. ihre noten sind gut und ihr elternhaus behütet. trotzdem lernt sie bereits in frühen jahren eine seite vom leben kennen, die man niemals erleben möchte. sie gerät in eine emotionale abhängigkeit zu einem jungen mann, der nicht nur ihren körper, sondern auch ihre seele verkauft.

ein roman über emotionale gewalt, zwangsprostitution, verstörende rituale und eine parallelgesellschaft, die sich mitten unter uns befindet.

teil 1 von 3

text:
flip your perspective.⠀
⠀⠀
i've put more thought into the idea of karma - what goes around comes around. doesn't that just sound threatening? and for all of the nastiness i've experienced in what feels like several lifetimes -- what did i do in a past life to "deserve" that? or is it that there is a wonderful life, full of love and abundance awaiting me?⠀
⠀⠀
i'm not sure i believe in karma -- but you know what i do believe in? being a good f-ing person who gives a damn about others. that no matter the hurt and pain that fills my soul, i can say to it -- i honor you, but you don't own me anymore. these stories are a part of me, but they are not my definition or narrative.⠀
⠀⠀
we are all stronger than we think.⠀
⠀⠀
surround yourself with people who support the loud, wild, intense, passionate version of yourself. they’re the same ones who support your quiet, reserved side. ⠀
⠀
flip your perspective.⠀

text:
the day i didn’t kill myself ✖️ i made this video instead. (this is the hardest post i’ve had to write all week) #tbt tahoe last year
story >>... i was in lake tahoe last year at a women’s retreat.  i was so lost in my own pain that i went for a drive as i often did to clear my head. everything inside of me wanted to end it, i had to fight those thoughts away, but my fighting power was weak. and so was my faith. instead of letting go of my life and the steering wheel, i parked my car on this turnout, propped my phone on the license plate of my car, and did what i always did as a kid when i was going thru pain .... i made art. ⚜️
.
this video marks the end of a long fight with depression and the beginning of holding on tightly to my life. .
🎵“nothing’s gonna change my world, nothing’s gonna change my world.” .

text:
i can’t take credit for the following! i outright stole from another post. and ps buy my book on amazon. it’s a poetry memoir of my life as a survivor of sexual assault and domestic violence and neglect. ❤ history of my heart: my journey thru domestic violence https://www.amazon.com/dp/1723974293/ref=cm_sw_r_cp_api_a53vbbwh1hxt4

from danielle muscato-- how to protect yourself from false rape allegations -- i'm seeing a lot of scared men right now. my heart aches for you. i get it: you're just trying to go about your day when in a mere instant, your whole life could be turned upside down. it's a scary world—you could lose everything, just because you were at the wrong place at the wrong time.

with that in mind, i present my top 10 tips for staying safe from false rape accusations:

1. if you go to a party, either have only one drink, or only drink soda or water, so you can keep your wits about you. never get tipsy around people you don't know and trust fully—it could come back to haunt you later. even around people you fully trust, remember that most false rape allegations come from people you know. be vigilant!

2. use the buddy system, so you always have a witness! only go to the bathroom with a friend, or ideally with a group of friends. always have a friend walk you to your car, in case you run into a strange woman in the parking garage. never go camping or hiking or biking or running or even just walking alone. never go to a bar or concert or party or event alone; that is just asking for it.

3. if you're going out anywhere, make sure you text the specifics of your plans to at least one or two trusted friends, in case they need to verify your whereabouts to police later. you may also consider using a location sharing app so you have proof of where you were and when.

4. if you're going to exercise, make sure that you bring a friend, or even better, just exercise at home. never go through a park alone. there might be a woman there who could accuse you.

5. when you're heading to class or work, never listen to music or podcasts on headphones. you need to listen carefully to your surroundings to make sure no woman is accusing you of anything.
#metoo

text:
i’ve been contemplating posting this. however i think more awareness to issues that are constantly occurring should be made.
a year exactly today marks my #metoo story.  this experience left me feeling like a shell of my existence, i felt robbed of my identity. it changed my future and inevitably traumatised me. but a year has gone by and i am starting to feel the pain ease off. i am starting to learn that i can overcome this, and that i am not alone. thank you to the people who checked up on me, more then once. thank you to the people who were there for me when it was a challenge to be. thank you to the people who tried to understand the pain i was feeling rather then walking away. my friends and family give me strength and today, i feel strong. i feel empowered and proud and i am learning to love myself and my body again. i hope this can additionally comfort anyone struggling. positivity really is contagious !😊

text:
manche dinge brauchen zeit. 
und das ist der grund, warum ich es jetzt sage.
.
weil jetzt der richtige moment ist, um zu sagen:
.
ich habe sexuelle gewalt und missbrauch erlebt.
und ich spreche seit 5 jahren darüber.
bisher nicht öffentlich. 
aber mit mir, mit tätern und betroffenen und mit meinen liebsten. .
und wenn es eines gibt, was ich dir mitgeben kann, dann würde ich mir wünschen, dass wir alle 2 dinge verstehen:
.
wir sind nicht allein. 
auch wenn es noch so einsam und dunkel scheint,- wir sind nicht allein! 
auch wenn wir einsam und allein waren, als es passierte: wir sind heute nicht einsam und allein. 
du und ich und jede verdammte dritte frau ist nicht allein.
.
wir sind nicht allein. .
und es gibt keinen grund es nicht zu sagen. es gibt keinen grund dafür, täter zu schützen und sich selbst dafür zu opfern. .
keinen einzigen verfi**** grund, mit seiner lebendigkeit, seiner wahrheit, seiner selbstbestimmung dafür zu zahlen, was andere getan haben! 
nie wieder. niemals. nie. .
in liebe zu mir und zu dir. 
ich sehe dich. 
pia .
#metoo #gegensexuellegewalt #gegenmissbrauch #wirsindnichtallein

text:
today will be the last conjunction of the moon and jupiter in scorpio for about 12 years. by the time the moon makes another 28 day cycle to scorpio again, jupiter will have moved onto sagittarius. otherwise, expanding (jupiter) on emotional truths (moon) will no longer have the framework of excavation, frankly death, flushing and eliminating out the diseased and moving on in that consistent and essential cycle (scorpio). the beauty of this jupiter in scorpio time has been the force of how we’ve had to get real about how in western society we’ve traded using sexuality as a power source to harm those we could assert power over instead of letting sexuality bring us closer. without clearly examining how toxic and separating our cultural sexuality is, we all frankly face death without hopes for transformation. on this last conjunction, cheekily positioned on national coming out day, i hope that your stories that have had to hold your sexuality alongside saying #metoo have been honored, and that you’ve felt more emotional safety by shedding light on the dark in the last year.
.
.
#nationalcomingoutday #mooninscorpio #jupiterinscorpio #moonconjunctjupiter #libraseason #instagay #instaqueer #lgbt #queerastrology #yourdailytransit
name: Laurence Jones

today will be the last conjunction of the moon and jupiter in scorpio for about 12 years. by the time the moon makes another 28 day cycle to scorpio again, jupiter will have moved onto sagittarius. otherwise, expanding (jupiter) on emotional truths (moon) will no longer have the framework of excavation, frankly death, flushing and eliminating out the diseased and moving on in that consistent and essential cycle (scorpio). the beauty of this jupiter in scorpio time has been the force of how we’ve had to get real about how in western society we’ve traded using sexuality as a power source to harm those we could assert power over instead of letting sexuality bring us closer. without clearly examining how toxic and separating our cultural sexuality is, we all frankly face death without hopes for transformation. on this last conjunction, cheekily positioned on national coming out day, i hope that your stories that have had to hold your sexuality alongside saying #metoo have been honored, and that you’ve felt more emotional safety by shedding light on the dark in the last year.
.
.

text:
5 years ago today my life changed forever. i started on a journey that beat me down physically mentally emotionally spiritually- and still does. i fell in love with a man who didn’t love me back like he said. i’ll just keep it simple and say that. my point is this- if you would have asked me 5 years ago if i would see myself standing where i am today the answer would be without a doubt “no way” for many reasons. i found strength in weakness, i found life in pain. i lost so much but i found out alot of things about myself- some that are true and some that definitely are not. and i still can’t catch my breath some days but somehow i make it. my grandma and dad have instilled in me “just when you think you have it bad someone else has it worse” and thank god they did because i don’t know where i’d be without that concept. that faith. so for everyone who reads this you can do it. i promise. you can survive loss after loss after loss and still do it. it hasn’t been a fun five years- but it’s been five years. so here’s to the next. interestingly enough it’s international girl day today. yeah- makes sense. 
#myjourney #writersofinstagram #innerself #rise #enddomesticviolence #metoo #standwithsurvivors #survivor #thriver #narcissisticabuse #blogger #bloggersofinstagram #lovehurts #warrior #strong #strongwomen #iamthestorm

text:
october. the time of spiritual beginnings and exploration continues! avert your eyes if i'm burning too brightly for your sensitivities. this is me and i've been hiding it for way too long. 
i have a #confession to make. 
i recently watched what we do in the shadows for the 1,000th time and even though it made me laugh and even creeped me out here and there, i also felt drawn in by the characters for a few different reasons. 
nope. there i go again, dancing around a topic i'm afraid will make people uncomfortable. okay, i'm going to be honest. there is something #erotic about being scared. and i'm not talking about interview with a vampire or trueblood were-creature kind of sexy. i'm talking about the seduction of danger and the unknown. there's a reason why we have such a strong attraction to the unknown. anything can happen. sometimes you're disappointed but other times your mind is blown. i accept both outcomes, chalk it up to experience and move on. 
i have another confession. i also enjoy #horror #erotica. i realized a long time ago that if eroticism and horror share the same taboo elements and are relegated to the fringe of what is tasteful and generally acceptable in our society, why not seek out individuals that have merged the two?

i can barely find friends who love horror on the level i do. in an article i read recently on the ringer, the author writes, "...horror movies are among the least respected forms of entertainment in the world. in some ways, that’s the point—they are the darkness behind the door, the awfulness in the far reaches of our imagination. they aren’t proper." the same can be said of erotica.

and thus, my third and final confession, at least for today. i'm taking a stab at it, so to speak. i've been writing for myself for years for shits and giggles have received positive feedback with some constructive criticism here and there. this, however, will be my first attempt at combining two genres i love in a medium and perspective i have ravenously consumed in the past but have never made an effort to create...until now.
name: It's just me!

i can barely find friends who love horror on the level i do. in an aicle i read recently on the ringer, the author writes, "...horror movies are among the least respected forms of enteainment in the world. in some ways, that’s the point—they are the darkness behind the door, the awfulness in the far reaches of our imagination. they aren’t proper." the same can be said of erotica.

and thus, my third and final confession, at least for today. i am taking a stab at it, so to speak. i have been writing for myself for years for shits and giggles have received positive feedback with some constructive criticism here and there. this, however, will be my first attempt at combining two genres i love in a medium and perspective i have ravenously consumed in the past but have never made an effo to create...until now.

text: i haven’t said much about life in the u.s. recently because it’s been an incredibly overwhelming amount of shit to process and i still can’t say i’ve properly dealt with it. it’s a super stressful political climate to be living in and kavanaugh’s nomination is so soul-crushing, i can’t even put into words what it’s like to have yet another rapist in a position of power. in an episode of @hiddenbrain they have a wonderfully informative discussion about the concept of horizontal violence and the fact that the #metoo movement grew out of having this president - i recommend listening. this movement has given me new role models like #drchristineblaseyford but i still feel as helpless as the sculpture in this picture. vote this november!! i have to say that knowing today is the #internationaldayofthegirl feels sad because we really don’t let girls be girls in this society. also, thank you @badgirlgonegoode and @stmcghee for inspiring me from afar with your protest attendance and resilience 💕

text: today is #internationalgirlsday and tomorrow marks 🖐🏻 years since i was attacked and sexually assaulted. i fought. i won. my attacker is behind bars because my jury of peers believed me and i had the proof so many people demand. most women aren’t as lucky as i am - some women face their attackers every day at work or at home or may never know who hurt them. every year i hope that i won’t have to use this anniversary to post a reminder to people that women aren’t objects, that women and girls deserve every opportunity that men do, and finally that women are smart, strong, and resilient. unfortunately, it seems every year my message is needed more than ever. 5 fingers for each year i have grown stronger makes a fist. this is the fist that i fought with and will continue to fight with because we are not giving up. #believewomen #fightlikeagirl #metoo #fighttowin

text:
venus retrograde in scorpio

she travels to the depths. to the parts unseen and unheard.
parts i’d rather keep locked away,
but parts that need to breathe nonetheless.

she whispers: even the smallest trespass counts.
coaxing out the memories as they flood to my consciousness.
it counts because it happened, even if i don’t remember the details how.

in a world of “not enough,”
my pain and my trauma is valid,
no matter how big or how small.

every unwanted lingering stare,
every hug that pulled me in too close,
every brush up against my body.

every grope,
every grab,
every encroachment on my being.

every insult,
every insinuation,
every joke that crossed the line.

all the humiliation,
all the harassment,
and all the harrowing assaults on my body.

i give it all back now. back to where it came from.
i refuse to carry the weight of your sins,
for this is no longer my burden bear.

when i breathe oxygen to the stifled memories,
and provide space for them to exist,
i move through my pain and transmute all of their transgressions.

venus in scorpio is my shamanic healer.
singing over my bones she digs up what i’ve pushed down.
rattling me to my core as i reclaim what is mine.

and with that, she helps me swim back to the surface a changed woman.
one who is no longer afraid to speak truth to her story.
and one who can find beauty in her pain.

text:
in the light of recent events, the controversial claims, and the raged male population: this post if for you.
i see many fragile egos hurt and many men coming forward trying their sheer best to falsify the victim claims surrounding the #metoo movement. why, sir? why is it so hard to believe? why do you point blank refuse to even hear these women out? are you going to don on the same disbelief when your sister or daughter comes to you and tells you that she was harassed by your friend/uncle/acquaintance?
let me clear it out for you:
#metoo is real.
#timesup is also real.
#webelieveher is also real.
yes, sometimes even the most pious ones can turn out to be complete perverts but here's the thing: no woman will tarnish her reputation for the sake of seeking attention. 
here's another thing: it requires nothing to turn into a predator. it's just a whim. so yeah, the uncle or the celebrity (whom you've never met but are vouching for as though he's your chachi ka beta) are also very much capable of harassing/molesting a woman. it's a clever of game of timings and circumstances, sometimes where it becomes too late for the victim to realise what he/she's going to get.
why speak after all these years, you ask? it's never too late. every person is different. every person's mental capability is different. some gather courage in that very minute, and kick the shins of their predator, whereas it takes months or maybe even years for another person to gather enough confidence.
please. please stop making fun or belittling the brave women who're coming forward with their stories. you are not only making her guilty for finally doing the right thing, but also closing down the ways for women who still are fighting everyday, plucking courage bit by bit.
appreciate them, because it takes your everything to speak the truth, specially when the truth governs around another person.
yes, ali zafar can be a harasser. yes, faisal edhi can be a pervert. yes, junaid akram can be a predator. stop defending men just because they're men and the allegations against them are by women. no body keeps a camera strapped at all times to provide enough evidence to satisfy your male ego.
shukria.

text:
today is international day of the girl. #wecandobetter

honestly... the last few weeks have been disgraceful. i am ashamed to say i have wanted to give up. i am ashamed to say i have wanted to not participate in this sham anymore. my heart is broken. i look around at people i thought i respected and see their weakness on full display. so many cowards. so many women and men who stand proudly and smugly at the fact that they let every little girl in their lives down. they have ensured that these little girls will not turn to them when they need their support the most. they have ensured that the little boys in their life won't understand accountability. they are regressive failures. but in this sea of weakness, i will not give up and drown. i will hold out my hand to all of those kids who have been let down by these enablers. thank you to the real men and women in my life who have stood up and put out your hand this week. you are the definition of strength and hope. and for those who have not... i see and hear you too. and i will be there to pick up the pieces of those hurt by your negligence and destruction.

text:
when i was in 8th grade, i was sexually assaulted in my social studies classroom. i didn’t understand and i told the administration because i knew it was wrong, however the guy was very popular and close with the dean and so they let him get away with it. they told me not to talk to anyone about it for “my safety” yet he went around telling anyone who’d listen vicious lies about me. it was the most confusing and difficult time of my life. when the #metoo movement started, i was overjoyed and felt so safe and not alone. now my favorite girl group is coming out with a song about sexual assault and the #metoomovement and it’s everything to me. 
i don’t think any of the girls will see this, but if you do, thank you so much. you mean so much to me and i am so thankful for you.
name: 💓Woman Like Cas💓

text: @camila_cabello just dropped a cool music video for her song #consequences - here is a rendition of my favorite part. i never used to understand why some friends would stay in bad or abusive relationships, but as i get older i understand more and more the depths that emotion can pierce. i understand how you can easily mask pain with contentment, and force yourself to only see the good and ignore the bad - because when it is good, it is really good. it is inexcusable when abuse and assault happens from someone you don’t know, and with recent world events, it is clear that no one is spared, regardless of gender. but - it is even worse when it happens by someone you know, or love. love is beautiful, it is kind. it can be complicated, but it should never hurt. love should not have consequences. today is #dayofthegirl #internationalgirlchildday - raise them well x

तनुश्री दत्ता की ओर से  नाना पाटेकर पर लगे यौन शोषण के आरोप के बाद भारत में #metoo का मामला जोर पकड़ चुका है. नाना पाटेकर के मामले में बोलने के बाद अब रेणुका शहाणे ने आलोक नाथ पर लगे आरोपों के बारे में रिएक्शन दिया है. उन्होंने 'हम आपके हैं कौन' में आलोक नाथ की बहू का किरदार निभाया था. रेणुका ने टीवी एक्ट्रेस दीपिका अमीन का समर्थन किया, जिन्होंने कहा है कि इंडस्ट्री में सबको पता है आलोकनाथ शराबी हैं, जो महिलाओं का उत्पीड़न करते हैं. पूरी जानकारी के लिए लिंक पर क्लिक करें: https://bit.ly/2edfrir

text:
on this international day of the girl i can't help but reflect on what it means to be a girl in today's world. 
some days i look at the news headlines and think "damn,  we've made no progress at all" and it's tempting to feel discouraged but then i look around and see women rising up, coming together, saying me too, saying no, saying enough! 
reaching out to each other, helping each other unpack our baggage, sharing our wisdom learned from hard fought battles. teaching each other how to rise and i feel more inspired than ever to continue my work mentoring, supporting and challenging women to take control of their lives. to create and live a life that they themselves have chosen, not some life that others decided they should live. 
i feel inspired to continue supporting and helping all three of my beautiful granddaughters grow and into the powerhouses they are. to claim that power and to use it to make this world a better place for all the beautiful women who will come after them. 
i think of my daughter in laws, girlfriends and all the other women i know who do the impossible every single day! love and be there for the people in their families, support and honour the women in their lives, walk dogs, do housework, the shopping and still manage to hold down full time jobs! 
i think of the awesome women i know south of my border who have been resisting for almost two years now and refuses to stop until the disgrace that resides in the white house is gone. i hold a special place in my heart for you ladies!! 💞👊💥 i am humbled and awed by your commitment and power. 
what does it mean to be a girl in today's world? it means to finally claim our place in this world and do everything within our power to bring love, kindness, healing and compassion to every corner of this beautiful planet we call home. 
love and blessings to each and everyone of you, my beautiful, amazing soul sisters! ❤️🙏🏻💞😘👊💥💫 #internationaldayofthegirl #girlpower #rise #createalifeyoulove #beyourself #yourbeautiful #lifecoachingforwomen #empoweringwomen #womenempowerment #overcome #strongwomen #soulsisters #ourtime #metoo #grandaughters #kindness #nicugrad #24weekers #preemiepower #twins #gratitude

text: i took this photo in the bathroom of the @thestandard hotel about 10 mins before i was sexually assaulted by susanne bartsch @bartschland at on top. my hands cannot stay still as i am typing this. i am shaking from anger and fear. i believe in the power of social media but i also know i want to share my story in case there is a survivor reading this: you are not alone. it is not your fault. you have autonomy over your own body. i believe you. my friends and i formed a classic dancing circle on the dance floor and began to get free, slowly letting the stresses of jobs, relationships, and health go as we moved our bodies in time to the beat. dancing is meditation for me. i let all thoughts pass through my mind with out judgment as i moved my body. the one significant thought i smiled at was that i was safe. as a queer black woman in a world that sees me as their blow up doll, their wildest fantasy come to life, i was safe. i was with others like me. i could feel free. not a moment later, @bartschland used the pointer finger to trail up the crack of my ass and lift the hem of my dress to expose my lower half to the entire dance floor, especially to those in her dancing circle standing behind me. i saw the lights of cellphone cameras and red. i immediately screamed don’t touch me please please please don’t touch me. stop fucking touching me as she chased me around the dance floor grabbing at my hair my arms my skin telling me i looked amazing. i broke away and ran to the roof. beyond triggered, i stood away from the crowd and tried desperately not to have a panic attack. my best friend found me. my other friends found us. i knew that if i did not confront susanne here and now nothing would ever happen. with my friends behind me, i saw her on the roof and confronted her. rather ironically, i politely waited for her to finish her conversation before telling her what she did was wrong. she interrupted me to offer me drink tickets. aside from the fact that i do not drink, how disgusting a reaction: to offer me a mind altering substance in exchange for sexual assault. what a way to enforce rape culture. then the anger came to the front. (continued below)

text:
hi bossbitches! sorry it's taken so long to make a post on this issue. i suppose we all needed a moment to reel from the ignorance and injustice that still plagues this country's justice system. 
like @trevornoah said, "trump's most powerful tool is that he knows how to wield victim-hood. he knows how to offer victim-hood to people who have the least claim to it" (i.e. white people & men). and it's exactly what he's taken advantage of and all these people in power have taken advantage of to defend kavanaugh and make the #metoo movement seem irrelevant. 
this administration has shown time and again that it does not care about what people go through regarding sexual assault. this battle has been lost, but the war is not over. we must keep having these conversations, taking action, and please if you are able to, make sure you register to vote and actually vote when the time comes for it!! #westillbelieveher #metoomovement #itsnotoveryet

text:
episode 29: teen october 2000⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
*cue creaking door and cauldron bubbles*

it’s that time of the year again my pretties...when goths can be themselves, you have an excuse to watch the craft five more times, and the freaks come out to play. relive your teenage halloween nightmares - complete with ghostly stories and reflections on the horrors of puberty. 
in other spooky news: girly mags was recently nominated for best podcast in now magazine’s readers choice 2018! didja vote and enter the contest? if so, listen up because the winner of the '90s-themed girly mags swag bag is...announced in the episode. 
come trick or treat with ghouly mags...if you dare. muahahahahaha!
available via link in bio, itunes, stitcher and wherever you get podcasts!

important note to our listeners:

each episode girly mags likes to share the cover of the magazine featured. however, this month’s cover featured a known abuser - actor nicholas brendon. girly mags is a huge advocate of women’s rights and ending domestic assault and sexual violence, and does not under any circumstances support anyone who has a history of abusing others. it is for this reason we have chosen not to include this episode’s cover. 
in the current climate we are encouraged, despite the weight against us, to speak our minds and our hearts and say no to people who hurt us, who hit us, who break us down, who call us ungodly names, who do not listen when we tell our truths. the world is starting to listen now. girly mags is listening. and we encourage you to be safe and ask for help if you’re in danger or if you’ve kept a secret that is hurting you. 
for all of the times you have stayed silent, now is the time to scream. 
if you are in danger, always call 911. 
for anyone who lives in canada that is looking for resources to talk about assault, you can visit endingviolencecanada.org/getting-help, and find anti-violence centres across the country at casac.ca/content/anti-violence-centres. if you reside in the us, you can visit thehotline.org, rainn.org or call the national sexual assault hotline at 800-656-4673.

we hear you. we believe you.

text:
happy international #dayofthegirl!

all around the world we are asking you to #standbyus #believeus #supportus.

we are living for the day where there's no #metoo, we don't need to #bringbackourgirls because no one took them, there's no need for #notbossy because we are allowed to be powerful, where #transwomen aren't being murdered, where #indigenous and #black women and girls aren't going missing.

where we are not seen as the spoils of war, the trophies for accomplished men, the second-class human, only the bearer of children, where our reproductive organs are not the site of male political debate.

no more #streetharassment, #maritalrape, #pinktax, #periodpoverty, #honorkilling, #fgm, #gbv and so many many more things that women and girls survive. 
i literally can't list them all. today i am grateful for #sisterhood, #feminism, #womanism, #blackgirlmagic, #solidarity, #inclusivity, #empathy.

i want to shout out the girls who defend other girls, believe other girls, support other girls, protect other girls, uplift other girls.

this is: @fatoumata_diawara__ and a lovely girls choir at the bill and melinda gates foundation, #goalkeepers awards, 2018.

text_retweet:
freedom from your abuser is only the first step. climbing back to life can be a long, slow, painful journey. 
the absolute best resource i have found to help survivors heal from psychological abuse is a book by @shannonthomas "healing from hidden abuse: a journey through the stages of recovery from psychological abuse." i strongly recommend it for anyone trying to relaunch a life after it has been intentionally and methodically destroyed by this kind of abuser. sometimes, the worst wounds cannot be seen. shannon focuses on identifying these wounds, understanding how they came to be, and then healing them fully so survivors can reclaim their truth. .
.
image
#repost @shannonthomas
• • • • •

also at barnes & noble, smashwords, ibook and itunes

text:
#metoo 
@adhyan96 ****************************** i am so happy to be seeing so many #metoo posts and how the snowball effect of one person speaking up openly about their experience with sexual harassment has led to many more having the courage to do so too. more than ever it brings to light the issues of consent, gender inequality and lack of education of the aforementioned.

there are many different kinds of harassment we should be aware of - including physical, verbal, non-verbal. and that many more ways we can brace ourselves against it if we know how to recognise it in the first place.

i did not know it at the time of clicking this picture, but looking at it today it suddenly reminded me of the time around a year ago, when i was sexually assaulted just a few streets down the road. i wrote about it then too.

i suppose i could consider myself lucky that it was only a case of groping, when so many women out there have been and are experiencing so many much worse situations. my love and support goes out to them and i hope to learn more about how i can help such survivors. i continue to educate myself on the topic. it's time for a change. one step or, if necessary, one post at a time.

text_retweet:
but really, it’s best practice to ask the owner if you can pet their dog. why aren’t we considering consent with kiddos? #bodyautonomy #consent .
#repost @sexpositive_families with @get_repost
・・・
anyone else encounter challenges with adult strangers or family members not respecting the body boundaries of the child you’re raising? they see a cute little face and feel entitled to put their hands, hugs or kisses all over them.... like one might do to a pet? 😒
.
well guess what!? you can absolutely intervene and advocate for a child’s rights, as a human being, to consent and body autonomy because children do not owe affection to anyone, not even to their parents/caregivers.
.
if we want the best chance for them to know that their body is theirs, not merely for others’ consumption or gratification... if we want to help minimize #metoo experiences that are based in consent violations, then speaking up to other adults when needed is how we can support the early consent education.
.
if you’re not sure what to say, something to the point can work best. “please do not touch (child’s name) without asking permission first. we are working hard to make sure they know about consent and that their body is theirs.” and if you have an infant or child whose communication may not be clearly expressed, again, just be direct, “please do not touch (child’s name) without asking me first. consent is important to us.”
.
and if the other adult is oppositional or challenges your response, that’s information that this is not someone who respects what you are doing and you can absolutely take steps to remove yourself and child from that situation. we do have choice, even when it feels like a tough choice.
.
children are not pets. they are humans who deserve the same respect often given to strangers. feel free to repost this if you need to send this message to folx in your world.

text: episode 5 of @neverthelesspodcast is out today. in it, we explore imagination and how the arts and sciences combine. the brilliant people whose voices you can hear on this episode include @missmayim (big bang theory fans you’ll like this!), @sophiathakur @sophiescott @monkeyandcrow @guerilla_jen #katemascarenhas. you’ll want to know their work, trust me. this artwork by @edenbrack (we miss you!). my favourite quote might be this from @monkeyandcrow: “lots of men in tech who were not really interested in gender balance until i think #metoo started happening and they started to think, oh, actually i have a daughter. and i was slightly troubled because obviously they probably had a mother, they may have had a partner, they may have had a sister or friends previously. however, the daughters are the change agents.” link to episode in bio. neat we released it on #dayofthegirl too.

text:
this is a highly personal post so if you feel uncomfortable or ashamed, please skip. thanks.
.
.
.

i don't feel ashamed. i've waited to share this openly and the time is now.

i did report after the 3rd time he raped me. he is my ex and his name is damon boykiw. 
why did i wait for the 3rd time? this is so funny to me that it's hard for people to understand. have you ever experienced trauma? did you think rationally after the fact? were your executive functions not impacted negatively? 
rape is traumatizing. i was hurt. we were living together and i was undertaking a process to get him out because he didn't want to leave. during that process, he raped me 3 times. the 3rd time was particularly violent and gross. a pattern was developing. gross. 
so after the 3rd time, i reported. i went to the hospital. guess what happened during interrogation. there were two detectives. the female played bad cop. she asserted that since we had consensual sex in the past, it wasn't a very strong case. 
basically telling me. if i've had or have a sexual relationship with a man - they are also allowed to rape me. she warned me that if they brought him in for questioning there was a chance he'd get furious and then i'd just have a bigger stronger rapist furious at me. seriously this is what happened.

i almost hate to post because the terrible message this sends out but it's my story and the state of this country.

the male cop was more compassionate and left it at an open case.

this is often what happens when women do report. i think the only solution is grassroots justice or a complete tower card of our current "justice" system. also, everyone needs to heal!! #metoo

.
"at the moment, there's roughly 1.1 billion young girls around the globe. and even though we've made great progress to make their lives better, there are still serious issues concerning their wellbeing: an average of 15 million girls marry before the age of 18 yearly; every 10 minutes, a teenage girl dies as a result of violence; and 130 million girls between the ages of 6 and 17 are not in school."andrea gonzales ramirez
.
.  ladies from all backgrounds and ages!!! happy international day of the girl!!! .
.
this is some of the data that inspired us to put together the #sheeplesslife programs and create the #sheeplesslifeacademy
.
today we celebrate you all, your inner child, the daughters of the past, the present and the future
.
invite your inner girl to play, and imagine all little girls and boys; the future adults of humanity, being guided lovingly but mostly feeling loved, respected and safe .
let your inner child be sheepless .
help us end inhuman acts towards our children for both boys and girjs; help us end sheepwalking on earth .
.
