text:
🌞🌞🌞 aus aktuellem anlass: 
@spiegel.online.de hat mit seiner sonderausgabe einen neuen hashtags ins leben gerufen. themen u.a.: wir feiern 100 jahre frauenwahlrecht 💪 (ja, so lange dürfen wir frauen uns noch nicht ins politische geschehen mischen). von der #metoo debatte hören wir auch schon seit einem jahr. wir finden die große aufmerksamkeit zum thema #frauenland wichtig und wollen euch erneut zum nachdenken und diskutieren unter unserem post anregen: 👇 findet ihr das reden um metoo immer noch unumgänglich oder sollte man vielleicht mit positiven hashtags kontern? wie wär‘s denn mit #frauenstolz ? 😜 bindet uns ein, erzählt davon, warum ihr stolz auf euch seid, weil ihr eine schlechte erfahrung überwunden habt. jede frau hat einen grund stolz auf sich zu sein! 💥
.
.
.
*werbung wegen markierung

text:
how incredibly amazing is this week’s issue of stylist magazine? the #madebygirls issue 👱🏻‍♀️👳🏽‍♀️👩🏾👧🏻🧕🏼👩🏼‍🎤👸🏼👩🏽‍💻🧒🏼👩🏿👳‍♀️ have you seen it? 🤗

grace, the editor of the made by girls issue, explains: “being a girl in 2018 is difficult. there is a constant pressure to look and behave a certain way and this has a huge impact on girls’ confidence and on our overall happiness.”
“being a girl today is also three other words: scary, exciting and empowering. while these words seem to contradict each other, i think that they are all very accurate.”
“i am growing up in a time where there seems to be a focus on empowering young women to be whatever they want to be, but there are still limitations that stop women from working their way to the top. girls frequently see negative press surrounding female leaders, which further reinforces the idea that they should settle for less than their male counterparts.” sums it up pretty accurately don’t you think. the next generation of women are facing some of the toughest mental challenges ever, whilst also embarking on potential futures with more power, respect, influence and endeavour than ever before. 
therefore as a woman i am choosing to support the next generation of women by;
1. being a positive role model 
2. supporting girls through @fit4life
3. being real and honest 
4. most importantly of all be kind - to myself and to others

what are you going to do? 
please tag women and organisations that are working hard to support and/or inspire girls 🙌🏽🎉💕 thursday 11 october marks the un’s international day of the girl child – a day created to increase the awareness of the gender inequality faced by girls around the world

#metoo #womensupportingwomen #thisgirlcan #girlstogether #movingforwardtogether #girls #whorulestheworld #girlsgirlsgirls #madebygirls

text:
international day of girls is an international observance day declared by the united nations; it is also called day of girls.  the observation supports more opportunity for girls and increases awareness of gender inequality faced by girls worldwide based upon their gender.  this inequality includes areas such as access to education, nutrition, legal rights, medical care, and protection from discrimination, violence against women and unfree child marriage.  the celebration of the day also “reflects” the successful emergence of girls and young women distinct cohort and developing policy,programming, campaigning and research”. #metoo#imwithher#girlpower
#girlsrock💕🌸👑

text: hello, my name is hal myers @halatious and this is my week to take over instagram from the los angeles center of photography (lacp). in an era of #metoo, it’s not surprising to see strong young girls like this also making a stand, even if it’s upside down. this image was taken at the wigwam hotel in holbrook, az – one of only two left along legendary route 66. besides the message, what i like about this picture is the complexity of different triangles that comprise the formal structure. about: my deep interest is in documentary, and especially street – but i employ a variety of styles to get at the heart of the subject matter in focus, whether it’s the synchronicity of a crowded marketplace or a simple expression that reveals the broader complexity of our shared human condition. more: ‪https://hrm.photography/‬ #lacpinstagramtakeover #lacp #losangelescenterofphotography #lacpmember #lacenterofphoto #photooftheday #photography #portrait #streetphotography #environmentalportrait #girlsrule

text_retweet:
the post is not about the picture.🙌
i believe in you, because i have been through too. not once or twice but uncountable times.
because i was 13,14,15 and was scared to let my single father know what i had suffered on streets while walking back home.
because i was a mature teenager to travel alone using public transport holding no knives or sticks to scare them.
because i was a beautiful woman to satisfy their hunger.
because they were taught we are weak, and we were taught to stay safe.
and guess what? 
we were indeed verry weak !!!!
but now we are not !
it's #timesup for the predators.
they're there everywhere , not just in the entertainment industry but all around the world.
.
i really appreciate and support the #metoo movement for a long listed reasons; for facing the reality atleast 100/365 days and i'm sure each & every woman reading this would have gone through the same in their lives. 
tag 5 such women you know who've discussed their worse experiences with you or share with me your story to be reposted anonymously or being tagged.
repost if you believe in it too..speak about it more.
#metoo #metoomovement #metooindia #speakup #women #risewomen #shareyourstory #womensvoices #nehalchudasama #missuniverseindia

text:
we watched the movie "soul surfer" last night (the bethany hamilton story, if you haven't seen it) and it was fabulous. what makes bethany's story inspiring is her determination to get right back to living life after she lost her arm very traumatically to a shark bite. it would be a devastating injury to anyone but to someone who is so athletic and had a bright future career as a professional surfer, it was not only devastating but threatened her very identity. 
often after loss, trauma, or tragedy, we have to reform our concept of who we are. after i left home at 19, i wanted to be a strong survivor, not an abuse victim. i didn't realize at that time that shutting out pain from the past gave it power over me instead of giving me power over it. to truly heal, we have to embrace what happens to us in life and accept that it will influence us. only then, do we have a choice in how it influences us. life hurts and bad things happen but our scars from life's wounds make us stronger when we learn to be grateful for them. 
for more on issues like this and other topics on reaching your potential in life and leadership, join me on my podcast "fearfully and wonderfully me." subscribe from your podcast channel of choice or listen here:
https://anchor.fm/riastory

#repost @curvesbecomeher
• • • • •
trigger warning 
#repost of video from @nowthisher 
when the #metoo movement started in the usa, i kept wondering about how this happens around the world. and i wondered if india would start calling men out as well. 
for the past few weeks,
@iamtanushreeduttaofficial has gone under fire for speaking about actor nana patekar misbehaving with her in the shooting of a song scene from movie horn ok please. she also called out the director of the movie chocolate for misbehaviour. the reactions ranged from ludicrous to incomprehensible to supportive. echoing the kavanaugh situation, people fired away asking why it took her 10 years to speak up. they claim this a setup to tarnish these men’s names. and on the heels of tanushree’s story comes forth more sexual allegations within the industry. 
to say bollywood is privileged is putting it mildly. and yet the outrage is a good sign that women are not hiding anymore. however this is a widespread problem in all vocations and areas in india, whether rural or urban. women who speak about our rights get called angry indian feminists but the truth is, our anger has been raging for a very long time. casteism and religious fundamentalism adds to this already messed up state of affairs. 
with the advent of instagram, south asian men are gaining infamy for their crass actions. you think you got it bad with their unsolicited dick pics and weird ass horn dog messages ... but it honestly is scary to be a south asian woman and i know this goes for women everywhere including here in singapore. men feel they have a right over you. and this is the indignant behaviour that is being seen from high profile bollywood actors like nana patekar and alok nath. 
we believe survivors. 
we need to listen and acknowledge that this has to be addressed.

#southasian #woc 
#metoo #believesurvivors 
#timesup #igsg #blogger 
#feminist #survivors 
#bollywood #feminism 
#intersectionalfeminism

to say bollywood is privileged is putting it mildly. and yet the outrage is a good sign that women are not hiding anymore. however this is a widespread problem in all vocations and areas in india, whether rural or urban. women who speak about our rights get called angry indian feminists but the truth is, our anger has been raging for a very long time. casteism and religious fundamentalism adds to this already messed up state of affairs. 
with the advent of instagram, south asian men are gaining infamy for their crass actions. you think you got it bad with their unsolicited dick pics and weird ass horn dog messages ... but it honestly is scary to be a south asian woman and i know this goes for women everywhere including here in singapore. men feel they have a right over you. and this is the indigt behaviour that is being seen from high profile bollywood actors like a patekar and alok nath. 
we believe survivors. 
we need to listen and acknowledge that this has to be addressed.

text:
if north dakota sen. heidi heitkamp loses her race, democrats can all but kiss their hopes of winning the senate goodbye. republicans have closed in on the seat, and think they’re on the cusp of delivering a knockout blow. heitkamp is down in public polls by a significant margin against her opponent rep. kevin cramer, but she recently hinted that she believes cramer could suffer from self-inflicted wounds. in a story published last weekend, cramer told the new york times that sexual assault accusations and the #metoo campaign against kavanaugh were a “movement toward victimization” of men. he also was scolded by canadians over his comments about new nafta negotiations.
🔸
“there’s a level of arrogance and rash statements that doesn’t reflect the typical north dakota, common-sense contemplative, work-together kind of attitude,” heitkamp said. “you can say all these crazy things, but sometimes the crazy things you say and how you behave has real consequences here.”
🔸
heitkamp’s allies say she’s far from done. they point to her universal name id, retail campaign skills and her surprise win in 2012 despite being down in the polls. heitkamp’s numbers dropped by double digits during the kavanaugh fight, but dems say their polling shows her numbers recovering. heitkamp came out against kavanaugh shortly before he was confirmed–which also spurred a gush of online money to her campaign. link in bio for the full story. 📸ap photo

text: “2018 has become the year of ballet’s reckoning: in january, the new york city ballet lost its longtime director, peter martins, who stepped down following allegations of abuse and sexual misconduct, which he denies. two months later, in a headline worthy of the onion, les grands ballets canadiens announced "femmes," an evening of dance on the subject of women, without a single woman choreographer on the program. oregon ballet put on a similar, although less publicized, program. in april, paris opera ballet dancers claimed bullying, sexual harassment, and dissatisfaction with their director. recently, nycb has been in the news again since a former ballerina, alexandra waterbury, sued the company after three male dancers shared sexually explicit photographs of her without her consent; one of the three men named in the lawsuit resigned in august, and the other two were fired this month. according to waterbury’s lawsuit, the company made it possible for its male dancers to “degrade, demean, dehumanize and sexually abuse women.” “every time i see a little girl in a tutu or with her hair in a bun on her way to ballet class, all i can think is that she should run in the other direction,” waterbury told the new york times, “because no one will protect her, like no one protected me.” women’s contributions to ballet have historically been the most ephemeral: they are the archetypal ballerinas, whose careers depend on the constant vanishing point of dancing, over as soon as it happens. the parts of ballet that last past the moment of its occurrence — choreography, teaching, and artistic direction — have long been dominated by men. and this moment, which offers us a chance to have a mainstream conversation about the sexism of ballet, is also an opportunity to seriously consider what ballet’s future might look like. what needs to change to make it less damaging to women, while still preserving its value and beauty? and who needs to be more included in order to effect that change?” ellen o’connell whittet takes a look at the ballet world after #metoo. 📸: stephane de sakutin/afp/getty images

text: the concept of “yours in sisterhood” is simple: people read unpublished letters written to ms. magazine between 1972 and 1980. these people live in the same towns from which the letters were originally sent. information on the original senders beyond that postmark is unknown both to the readers and us. sometimes the readers simply read their letters; other times they muse on or respond to the words. director irene lusztig arranged for and filmed over 300 such readings in 32 states, and then winnowed them down to around two dozen. within the parameters that lusztig has established, the documentary, screened last month at the camden international film festival, finds many different ways to prod at and muse on feminism now versus in the 1970s. ms. magazine, with its pivotal role in second-wave feminism, exists here more as a symbol and jumping-off point. while some letters refer to specific articles in the magazine, we don’t hear their names or edition dates. removed from that context, we have the conversations from various years instead of their referents, and those conversations are then mixed into today’s discourse around feminism. in those meetings there are alternately affirmative demonstrations of how far society has come, dispiriting examples of how much some things haven’t changed, and striking contrasts in how the terms of certain issues have shifted. source: hyperallergic #documentary #documentaries #doc #ms #magazine #1970s #letters #sisters #feminism #feminist #woman #women #picoftheday #photooftheday #instalike #read #reader #movie #movies #film #films #change #progress #metoo #sisterhood #picoftheday #instadaily

text:
my mum being a middle class desi woman has always preferred rickshaws over cabs. 
my 17 year old self used to ask this question every single time - why????? to which she always said, "bunda kam az kam chalang to lga skta hai..." (one can at least jump off the vehicle anytime). i, being the logical wtf woman that i was (and still am thou) wondered k ye kya bat hui mtlb, cab to track bhi horae hoti hai, infact pura database hota hai driver ka and all that. while on the other hand rickshaw wala to rear mirror me guttka chabate hue dekh raha hota hai hume, ye zada disgusting nae hai? or dusra ye k agr koi situation hoti hai bhi to chalang lgana kitna dangerous hai bhae... lekin i never asked any of these questions to her, my medium of transportation is still careem/uber btw. 
phir khair kal hi rickshaw me bethne k ittefaq hua. beth kr i actually realized k she was right. with all the #metoo and #timeisup thing going on and men cursing women for speaking up after a decade... rickshaw k bht pros hain in any such situations. 
1. you are traveling with a rally of people around you which is alot better than traveling in a dabba with a driver alone who knows your address, phone number, and other whereabouts.
2. you can always gather the courage to kick/hit/hurt the creepy rickshaw wala jb k car me you are locked. 
3. you can scream or react in anyway, jump off the vehicle, gather people and anything like that. 
4. capitalist industry ko lollipop kra skte hain aap. 
5. best for broke people like yo desi wannabe artsy bitch. 
6. un mardon ko chilla ker involve krskte hain jin k ronay nae khtm horhe k "pehle kyun nae bola" ... itni fruitful existence hoti apki to kya hi bat thi bhai.

faqat 
apki sathi harassed behn .
.
.

text:
like the way media and film circles in tamilnadu are gathering storm now for #metoo after singer chinmayi blasted many including prominent lyricist vairamuthu, telugu industry is yet to see any such.

while some say that sri reddy has already showcased the #metoo thing here, some sexist remarks by our acts should be added to that tag. some popular actors who have passed sexist remarks in public events (film events) are back in discussion. 
1) nani's nadumu remark
none expected that hero nani would cross all the boundaries and talk about a heroine's 'nadumu' at "supreme" audio launch. "raashi you're very beautiful. when i watched 'supreme hero' (andam hindolam) song, i thought of whistling two times. the first it is being a chiranjeevi garu's song and the second time is when i got a glimpse of your 'nadumu'. 2) chalapathi rao's vulgar comment
at the audio launch of "rarandoi veduka chooddam", when the anchor asked chalapathi rao if women are really harmful, he stated that they are good for bedding. "pakkaloki panikostaru" is what he said. 
3) ali's benz circle comparison
speaking at a film event in vijayawada, comedian ali stated that samantha's 'nadumu' is like a benz circle. visually showcasing the waist area on himself, ali said, "that part from here to here, it looks like benz circle". later at size zero event, he stated that anushka looks like that hot jilebi and also spoke of her thighs. 
4) balayya's pregnant line
"my fans don't want me to just run around a heroine. they either want me to kiss her or impregnate her" said balayya at paisa vasool related event. his comment was severely criticised as he happens to be a sitting mla as well when he said that. 
5) megastar chiranjeevi's unwanted talk
of course, the film industry is showcasing only the glamorous side of heroines most of the time on the silver screen. but talking about that 'objectification' quite openly doesn't make any sense. at rachha audio launch he went on describing that tamanna's glamorous looks are stunning, and at dhruva prerelease event he called rakul preet voluptuous. that didn't go well with a section of feminist fans. 
#chiranjeevi #balakrishna #nani #chalapathirao #ali.

text:
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
4 years ago i went through a big breakup right around christmas. 4 years ago i was at a holiday work party. and 4 years ago i was sexually harassed. i too went through the #metoo movement. with more words than said.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
if you guys can read between the lines, then you can figure out what i went through. but the reality of it is that you never think it’s going to happen to you and then it does.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
i would have never though this was going to happen to me and it was around people i knew and was close with.  after it happened, i couldn’t fathom it. i replayed the events of the night over and over and where i had gone wrong.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
4 years ago this had changed my life. i’ve only ever told 5 people in my life what had happened to me back then and it took me a long time to get over it.i still think about it and cry sometimes. and when i do tell people, my throat closes up and gets super watery. i had to drop friends who were toxic out of my life because they knew about it and didn’t do anything to help me at the moment. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
this is where my real transition for my fitness journey started. after i went through what i did i was scared and confused and didn’t know what was going to happen next. even though my fitness journey started when i was 23. at that moment the aftermath of being sexually harassed put my goals into a new perspective.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
i no longer wanted to have men feel like they could own my body. i no longer wanted people to feel like they could just take advantage of me. so with fitness i was able to gain the confident and respect i wanted and no longer feel held back in my skin and no be proud of the work i put in it today. i have the body i deserve. 
i am now more comfortable in my skin no matter who makes remarks and i no longer feel so taken advantage of i can’t say something to stand up for myself because now i can and fitness helped me get through this point. #fitness #fitnessjourney #strongerthanmystruggles #gym #strong #fitgirl #fitspo #health #weightlossjourney

.

text:
this is a post i’ve been wanting to do for a while now, and with yesterday being #worldmentalhealthday, i think it’s the perfect context!
.
this is a line from a song by australian hip hop group the thundamentals. it struck a chord with me as soon as i heard it because of how subtlety profound it is.
.
loneliness is a hell of an emotion, think about it! it misleads is to believe that in the absence of other people filling a physical space, we are alone. even when there are other people around you, loneliness will convince you that you are set apart, an island unto yourself.
.
whether you’ve recently lost someone, are being abused, harassed or bullied, just broke up with your boyfriend, or feel as if you have no one who understands you - please know that being alone and being by yourself are two totally different concepts and that loneliness can turn your feelings toxic very quickly!
.
in this world of over 7 billion human beings, please trust that there is someone out there who understands what you’re going through! you don’t have to be “by yourself” by yourself.
.
as the song says, “when all you can do is feel like everyone else just know, you’re not alone you’re just by yourself, and you’re all that i think about!” there are ways you can reach out, know that there are people out there who care and can relate even if they don’t know you! know that there is no such thing as a singular occurrence in life, that there is nothing unique about your suffering! there is someone else who has or is experiencing what you’re going through!!! but as in all things, understanding yourself better, before the loneliness turns toxic, will help you out of a dark place!!!
.
you’re not alone, you’re just by yourself, and we’re blessed everyday. i love you and am here to help in any way i can 💯💯💯 #lessgo
.
#coachlaincares #worldmentalhealthday #thundamentals #youarenotalone #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #loneliness #alone #everybodyissomebody #helpisoutthere #suicideawareness #help #inspiration #awareness #metoo #maskuline
name: Coach Lain™ Tumble & Technique

text:
“boring.” that was donald trump’s instant verdict on the new york times’s blockbuster investigation into the rampant tax fraud and nepotism that undergirds his fortune. sarah huckabee sanders heartily concurred, informing the white house press corps that she refused to “go through every line of a very boring, 14,000-word story.”
welcome to a new political pr strategy premised on the shredding of the american mind — you don’t want to even try to read that interminable article; check out my twitter feed instead, and this viral video of me saying rabid things.
the times investigation, published as a standalone supplement on sunday, is about as boring as a car accident. it shows in lavish detail that trump’s creation myth is and always has been a work of fiction. no, he did not take a “very, very small” million-dollar loan from his father and use his deal-making acumen to parlay it into a $10-billion global empire, while paying the original loan back with interest.
trump has been sucking on a spigot of his father’s cash nonstop since he was in diapers, becoming a millionaire by middle school. according to the times, when all was said and done, “mr. trump received the equivalent today of at least $413 million from his father’s real estate empire, starting when he was a toddler and continuing to this day.” moreover, “much of it was never repaid.” as for the rest of the mythology, not only was he spending his father’s money, he blew much of it on disastrous deal after disastrous deal. only to be bailed out by his father’s millions time and time again.
rather than bothering to deny any of this, trump and his surrogates have simply spun a new creation myth. no longer the scrappy, self-made man, trump is being reincarnated in real time as the chosen son, with he and his father acting as partners in wealth creation. (continued in comments) 
#donaldtrump #trump #kavanaugh #wealth #inequality #metoo #berniesanders

alison leiby is a stand up comic and writer who's written for comedy central shows such as "the president show" and "the opposition with jordan klepper." i had her and my wife jess on the show to commiserate together about a dude named brett! -
originally hailing from the annapolis, maryland area, alison shares some insights into growing up with a politically aligned mother, her fears over the recent supreme court nomination and she asks about the direction of white guys in comedy! -
check out the latest ep of derek mansplains it all, "guys named brett", on @itunes , @soundcloud , and @spotify !  also, do not forget to check out the two hour special finale of "the president show" starring anthony atamanuik which airs on comedy central, monday october 22nd at 11pm.

text:
bruises fade. the unseen impacts of domestic violence last for decades. 
what you can see, can move you. what is invisible, or misunderstood, you might judge.

don't do that.

listen if they're ready to talk. stand by them if they're ready to leave.

help them find help when they're ready to heal. 
none of it is linear. none of it is on your timeline. healing takes time. lots of it.

if you or someone you know needs help:

rainn.org @rainn

thehotline.org 
#dva #metoo #whyididntreport #domesticviolence #domesticviolenceawareness #thehotline #rainn #october

listen if they're ready to talk. stand by them if they're ready to leave.

help them find help when they're ready to heal. 
none of it is linear. none of it is on your timeline. healing takes time. lots of it.

if you or someone you know needs help:

rainn.org ainn

thehotline.org

text:
good morning! 
the alliance experienced its first panel last night! kathleen hays was asked to talk about some of the unique challenges that indigenous women face. she told them about the #mmiw epidemic and that we don't know the statistics for women in sc, which is largely due to native american not being a race option on all police reports. she also talked about the importance of icwa and the need for icwa-style laws in sc. 
our next panel is next thursday. kathleen will be speaking about the #metoo movement and how this is an issue for indigenous women. 
check out the october’s events calendar to get all the information on the #metoo panel.

text:
#metoo ...this little girl's innocence has been stolen from her already. this little girl had already sat in a police station and recounted the memory of waking up to a man's hand in her underwear and what happened next. this little girl already had to make the decision to run to the phone and be killed or pretend she fell back asleep and wait for it to be over. this little girl dyed easter eggs the day after she was assaulted. this little girl will never be the same. this little girl will go on for the next 20 years living with complex ptsd for which she didn't know she had. this little girl will grow up afraid that she may die in her sleep (or worst..), afraid of the dark, afraid of men, afraid of the police...this scared little girl is me.
so on today, #dayofthegirl i ask you to stand up and vote. stand up for that little girl. stand up for me.
.
.
.

text:
m e  t o o
you looked in her direction 
she squirmed in her place 
you looked away 
she heaved a sigh of relief
.
you don’t know what happened last time someone looked in her direction, you’ll never know
.
you accidentally touched her in a crowded bus 
she snapped at you, you apologised 
you forgot about it but 
she forgot to sleep that night
.
you don’t know what happened last time someone touched her without her consent, you’ll never know
.
you walked down an alley behind her casually 
she sprinted the whole lane and ran away
you thought how weird, she on the other side was busy calming her nerves and racing heart down
.
you don’t know what happened last time she was alone on a deserted street, you’ll never know
.
you were at a party 
she was with you
you said the words
she brushed it off
.
you felt anger she felt disappointment.
“these are my feelings”, you said 
she left the place 
you cried a little
.
she cried a river
she gulped down her anti-depressants 
the words reminded her of the abuse and torture 
she stopped functioning for a day or two
you no longer care
.
you don’t know what happened last time, you’ll never know
.
you’ll never know 
you’ll never understand her awkwardness when you looked at her, 
you didn’t observe her trembling hands when you touched her,
you didn’t hear the heartbeats drumming inside her when you were behind,
you didn’t notice the sadness in her eyes.
.
and maybe you’ll never know because you never tried.
— nooriya 
#metoo #dayofthegirl

text:
these words can be true if we let them. life will always gift us opportunities if we are open to seeing them and unattached to how they might show up. 💖
.
on #worldmentalhealthday i reflect on my own journey that is just over a year old now -- one i never imagined i would take. i had no history of struggles with mental health. i consider myself strong and resilient. .

and like all humans, i am not immune to life's challenges. when i unwittingly dove headfirst into a major episode of late-onset ptsd last year as a result of domestic violence, sexual assault and a 15 year history of unhealthy romantic relationships, i realized my body had decided enough was enough.
.
ptsd was a blessing that finally demanded, very loudly, that i do the work once and for all in discerning what patterns i had unconsciously perpetuated that allowed space for these types of dynamics to repeatedly enter my life. and that, my friends, required some seriously heavy lifting. it was harder than any ultraendurance race i have ever done and harder than completing my doctoral degree. .

but i had built the tools for the job: i dove into my self-inquiry with the curiosity of a scientist, the tenacity of a pro athlete, and the guidance of an amazing somatic therapist, jess (@yotherarise). and even in the darkest times when i just wanted it all to go away, i held tight to the tiny seed inside of me that trusted none of it would be a waste.
.
and here i still am. one year "sober" from ptsd and toxic relationships. i am the healthiest, most joyful, and most alive that i have ever been. i lost a lot during that time, including my business and my identity as an athlete. and so i slowly and very intentionally rebuild. putting all i have learned into action. choosing only 100% alignment. and for all that i lost, i have gained infinitely more. .

today and every day, consider that your struggles may in fact be gifts in disguise. see them as an opportunity to know yourself and your innate brilliance more intimately. dive deep into your own soul, giving fear a smile and a wink on your way down. i promise what you will find is more vibrant than you could ever imagine. 💖
.
. 📷: @kurt.refsnider

text:
celebrating #dayofthegirl by thinking about the beautiful, inspirational, and strong women and girls that have shown me what it means to be a woman. they deserve the utmost praise. thank you to every woman that knows they can be anything they want to be. thank you to the women of color that go the extra mile to ensure the safety and success of little girls of color. thank you to the trans women that have proven to us that a woman is more than having a vagina, but someone who is powerful and themselves. thank you to the women who have put up a fight to have control over their bodies. thank you dr christine blasey ford. and thank you, most of all, to my mother who raised me to respect women. i’m one of the lucky guys that was able to grow up with a badass mom that knew what she wanted and worked for it. everyday we should be thanking women and girls. girls run the world!
.
.
.

text:
“it’s okay to be a glow stick. sometimes we need to break before we can shine.” 🌟 
a timely reminder today - on world mental health day - to ensure that life’s struggles only makes you stronger 💪🏻
this beautiful pic was taken by my hubby @chippieb and i was the ‘glow stick’ holding the torch lighting up the tree. at the time, we were actually on our way home from hospital after i’d badly burnt my hand in a silly mindless mistake while cooking  dinner. 
i’d been thinking about work and all the bullying and general crap so many of us endure every day. 
i don’t really talk about it. so many of us don’t. but, sadly, life isn’t all rainbows - as much as i wish it was! 🌈 
everyone - and i stress, everyone - is carrying their own burden, and that matters, it counts, and is just as worthy of acknowledgement as the next person! you matter. you count. 
so be kind to yourself. talk about it. and remember, it’s okay to ‘break’ sometimes, because sometimes you need to in order to re-find your inner shine! 🌟 💫 .
.

text:
yippiee yippie! it’s time to take out my hand bags from the closet, the baby is growing up too fast and is almost diaperfree and me ""diaper-bag free""! so, here i am - flaunting my bag and all that it carries these days.

taking up #28dayschallenge has brought some positive changes in me and not just my skin. i realised how i had forgotten things and hobbies i held so close to myself earlier, reading and self care being a couple of those things. after i took up this challenge, i also caught hold of this book (i have been meaning to read for years but failed). i took up @olayindia challenge last month and the olay total effects 7 in one anti-ageing cream has now become a part of my bag. i am not an everyday  make-up person, but a few things like a good day cream, lip liner, lipstick, kajal and perfume are a must carry for me.

looking good gives you confidence and that's what olay total effect 7 in one anti- ageing cream did to me, the blemishes have lightened substantially in these few weeks of usage. i love the natural glow i’m noticing on my skin.

do try it out to know for yourself! 
#olayindia  #skintransformation #stayallivee  #28dayschallenge #reborn #olayforallages  #totaleffectsdaycream #daycream #totaleffects

text:
today is international day of the girl. today (and all days) we recognize all girls who grew into women who made strides in changing history. we recognize those that have been strong through oppression and overcame obstacles no man or boy had to. today we recognize the girls who stand up to the boys. we recognize the young ladies who love ballet and those who dirt bike. we recognize the girls going into science, engineering, medicine- the roles that were once thought to be for boys and men only. we recognize the women who are part of the #metoo movement. those who have been assaulted and made to feel less than. we recognize and celebrate all the young girls that dream big- never stop, keep on keeping on 💕

text:
shame. it is such a tricky, slippery emotion to feel. we might start with guilt or frustration, but end up feeling ashamed - without knowing why.

thinking about a #metoo experience can evoke feelings of shame - because society has put the onus of every action or incident on the victim as much as (if not more than) on the perpetrator.

now, with #metoo stories pouring out, we are confronted with the stark reality that until recently, our collective silence enabled such misdeeds to be hushed up.

unpacking this feeling and exploring ways of addressing it can be therapeutic. start a conversation in your social circles to find a constructive way to channel this emotion, and speak to a mental health professional if the feeling persists.

#mentalhealthawarenessmonth #metoo
